    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that sounds good in theory, but it feels like a bit of a gamble for a single owner. if i have to raise my prices to cover the wages, won't my customers just stop coming? it seems like the \"increased spending\" argument assumes everyone is magically getting richer, whereas the risk of me going out of business is a very real, immediate math problem. isn't it a bit risky to prioritize those theoretical long-term benefits over the actual survival of small businesses right now?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are right to focus on immediate survival, as the risk of price sensitivity is very real for a new small business. The key is to view price increases not just as a cost pass-through, but as an investment in quality that justifies the new price point. Focus on providing a superior customer experience that makes your cafe a destination, rather than just a commodity, which helps customers accept moderate price adjustments.",
